{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Referred to as a \"Bayesian machine in action, \" this framework views the brain as an entity that not only infers from sensory input but also actively intervenes to minimize \"surprise, \" aligning its internal model with the external environment (Knill and Pouget, 2004) via perception and aligning the external environment with its internal model (Friston et al., 2016), via action.",
    "There is some debate with regards to the nature of \"action\" and its epistemological (Rescorla, 2015) connotations.",
    "It involves the way that organisms coming to know and understand their world being inherently linked to their actions within it.",
    "Knowledge and understanding therefore, are not just related to passive observation, but are constructed through active engagement with the environment.",
    "This debate has implications for attempting to understand epistemology in biological systems; knowing can be seen an embodied, dialogic process."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Referred to as a \"Bayesian machine in action, \" this framework views the brain as an entity that not only infers from sensory input but also actively intervenes to minimize \"surprise, \" aligning its internal model with the external environment (Knill and Pouget, 2004) via perception and aligning the external environment with its internal model (Friston et al., 2016), via action.",
    "There is some debate with regards to the nature of \"action\" and its epistemological (Rescorla, 2015) connotations."
